04838nam a22007215i 9780271078243DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710782437 a10.1515/97802710782432doi  a(DE-B1597)584049  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0150802bisacsh04a704.9/49972231 aMarkey, Lia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagining the Americas in Medici Florence /cLia Markey. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b68 color/58 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne The New World and Italy in the Early Sixteenth Century -- tTwo A Turkey in a Medici Tapestry -- tThree The Americas in the Guardaroba Nuova -- tFour Francesco's Exchange and Documentation of American Nature -- tFive The Stanzino and the Representation of the New World -- tSix Between Ethnography and Fantasy in Ferdinando's New World -- tSeven The Florentine Codex and Buti's Frescoes of Amerindians -- tEight Stradano's Invention of the Americas -- tNine The Americas Both Real and Imagined -- tConclusion: Vicarious Conquest -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first full-length study of the impact of the discovery of the Americas on Italian Renaissance art and culture, Imagining the Americas in Medici Florence demonstrates that the Medici grand dukes of Florence were not only great patrons of artists but also early conservators of American culture.In collecting New World objects such as featherwork, codices, turquoise, and live plants and animals, the Medici grand dukes undertook a "vicarious conquest" of the Americas. As a result of their efforts, Renaissance Florence boasted one of the largest collections of objects from the New World as well as representations of the Americas in a variety of media. Through a close examination of archival sources, including inventories and Medici letters, Lia Markey uncovers the provenance, history, and meaning of goods from and images of the Americas in Medici collections, and she shows how these novelties were incorporated into the culture of the Florentine court. More than just a study of the discoveries themselves, this volume is a vivid exploration of the New World as it existed in the minds of the Medici and their contemporaries. Scholars of Italian and American art history will especially welcome and benefit from Markey's insight.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArt, ItalianxThemes, motivesxItalyxFlorence. 0aArt, ItalianzItalyzFlorencexThemes, motives. 0aArt, RenaissancexThemes, motivesxItalyxFlorence. 0aArt, RenaissancezItalyzFlorencexThemes, motives. 0aIndian artxCollectors and collectingxHistoryx16th centuryxItalyxFlorence. 0aIndian artxCollectors and collectingxHistoryx17th centuryxItalyxFlorence. 0aIndian artxCollectors and collectingzItalyzFlorencexHistoryy16th century. 0aIndian artxCollectors and collectingzItalyzFlorencexHistoryy17th century. 0aIndian artxInfluence. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311074524540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271078243zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271078243423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271078243.jpg  a978-3-11-074524-5  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  